<h1>Indoor Plants</h1>
<div>
<img src="wfa.jpg" alt="image of orchid" style="float: right; width: 25%; padding: 10px;"> 

<h2>Easy difficulty</h2>
<p>The easiest route that most people take when buying their first indoor plant is buying a tropical plant which is a great option since
they require watering around onece per week which is pretty good. I beleive that these plants are better than succulents even though they need to 
be watered more frequently since it's easier to forget about succulents while sitting in a corner, these plants will not die after being neglected 
up to a month depending on the plant.
</p>
<h3>My favorite tropical plants</h3>
<ul>
	<li>Pilea pepperomia</li>
	<li>anthurium</li>
	<li>Pothos</li>
</ul>
<p>These are great plants because they are nice to look at and don't require too much attention</p>
<img src="wfo.jpg" alt="image of orchid" style="float: right; width: 25%; padding: 10px;"> 
<h2>Medium</h2>
<p>I consider a medium difficulty plant to be a plant that needs to be watered more frequently, around once every 3 days
these.
</p>
<h3>My favorite medium difficulty plants</h3>
<ul>
	<li>Peace lilly</li>
	<li>turtle vine</li>
	<li>Alocasia Pink Princess</li>
	<li>Orchid</li>
</ul>
<p>I consider these options medium difficulty since there is a greater consequence if you neglect them, for example the leafs of the peace lilly will droop,
the tiny leaves of the turtle vine can burn or turn brown and can become a tedious task to pluck them out and the alocatia pink princess
begins to sweat water droplets if overwatered and will droop and fall which can cause the stem to break and cause a difficult recovery.</p>
<p>I consider orchids a medium difficulty plant since many people will give up on them, their blooms don't last very lond and look slightly bald a lot of 
the time, they also need fertalization around once a month, and people don't alwayse treat them correct which is why they end up dying, so this is not a 
great first plant, however a beautiful flower to own after familiarizing with the plant world.</p>
</div>
